Title: Captain America: Civil War Official Trailer #1 (2016) - Chris Evans, Scarlett Johansson Movie HD
Comment:
Just got back from seeing the film. Ultimately, I rank it 4.5 stars out of 5. I'll admit that there are some really brutal parts in it that make the film hard to see, knowing that the heroes are fighting each other; but in the end, it proves to be currently the most mature installment of the Marvel Cinematic Universe to date. Combine a very politically astute plot and clever character development with the all-traditional groundbreaking sound and visual effects and graphics and a musically enthralling score by Henry Jackman, spectacularly executed action and battling sequences, and the addition of brand-new heroes to the Marvel Cinematic Universe straight from the comics to the silver screen, (most notably the ass-kicking Black Panther), and you can start to visualize the true potential of Captain America: Civil War, the final installment of the Captain America trilogy and the thirteenth installment of the M.C.U.

(And, speaking as a nineteen-year-old freshman in college, I just find it somewhat amusing to know that the studio cast a nineteen-year-old, Tom Holland, as the new Spider-Man; he was REALLY good in the role, but speaking on behalf of my being more of an Amazing Spider-Fan, I don't really think that he'll ever reach the amazing heights of Andrew Garfield's version -- but he is, however, like Garfield,  SIGNIFICANTLY better than Tobey Maguire -- ultimately ranking Holland as the runner-up, with Garfield as the legend, and Maguire as the rookie).

So, there's my perspective. Whether you agree with me or not is entirely up to you; and in the end, I'll pay you my respects to that.

Iron Man is very cool but after 4 movies I am sick of the terrible jokes and humor but I did really enjoy the important deeper moments in the movies. Comment:
"So was I."
Bull-shit.
You and Steve have at best been rivals, trying to one up each other, and only getting along because of the team initiative. Hell, Cap was thoroughly against you in Avengers 1 and 2 for your attitude problems alone, and in creating Ultron without even a 2nd thought, you made things if anything worse.
Just digging through MCU lore, but maybe a more valid reason to go after Cap if because he's defending the man who, oh I don't know, KILLED YOUR FATHER.
Forced emotions that didn't exist prior are the same regardless of setting, story and characters.
Batman v Superman has a much better grounding reason for those 2 to go against each other, mainly through Batman going after Superman initially and snowballing from there.

Crossbones snipes at him while Sharon Carter, who has been brainwashed by Doctor Faustus, (and Cap's girlfriend) posing as a S.H.I.E.L.D. psychiatrist, delivers the killing shot. S.H.I.E.L.D. director Tony Stark and Black Widow hunt Captain America's murderers. Falcon, Captain America's old partner, follows his own leads to find the killers. Meanwhile, Bucky Barnes decides to kill Tony Stark, blaming him for Captain America's death.

For anyone here who is new to the MCU and wants to watch this movie here is the List of the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU) films in order of release:

PHASE 1:
Iron Man (2008)
The Incredible HULK (2008)
Iron Man 2 (2010)
THOR (2011)
Captain America: The First Avenger (2011)
The Avengers (2012)

PHASE 2:
Iron Man 3 (2013)
THOR: The Dark World (2013)
Captain America: The Winter Soldier (2014)
Guardians Of The Galaxy (2014)
Avengers: Age of Ultron (2015)
Ant-Man (2015)

Those are ALL, watch them in that order, and get ready for Phase 3 which is the FINAL, and Last phase of the MCU.

PHASE 3:
Captain America: CIVIL WAR (2016)
Doctor Strange (2016)
Guardians Of The Galaxy Vol. 2 (2017)
Untitled Spider-Man film (2017)
THOR: Ragnarok (2017)
Black Panther (2018)
Avengers: Infinity War- Part 1 (2018)
Ant-Man and the Wasp (2018)
Captain Marvel (2019)
Avengers: Infinity War- Part 2 (2019)
Inhumans (2019)

Comment:
Here is why these two heroes are leading different factions of Avengers.
Iron Man believes that being unregulated could be dangerous for everyone around him although he and his fellow Avengers have worked hard together to save people before.
Captain America believes that registering for government service will go against the morals that heroes stood for as well as realising that the government could end up following a corrupt system that will result in the deaths of many people worldwide.
The hero who I believe is right is Captain America. He will always be my favourite Marvel superhero from now on.

Title: Captain America: Civil War Official Trailer #1 (2016) - Chris Evans, Scarlett Johansson Movie HD
Comment:
This movie couldn't be any more similar to Dawn of Justice yet bet so different at the same time.

Dawn of Justice is going to be big, and rightfully so- after all, Superman's battle against Zod and his followers was seen around the world.

The motivations of the respective sides are fittingly grandiose:

Superman: "I'm just here to help, but I think this Bat-man vigilante is going to get in the way of that."
Batman: "This alien has too much power. He needs to be stopped."

As a result, Superman is going to be targeting Batman (as Clark Kent) as much as Batman will be targeting Superman.

For Civil War, however, it's a much more personal affair. Steve is only doing what he's doing because he knows that Bucky's crimes as the Winter Soldier are immense. Bucky might even be executed, and since he's the only thing Steve has to his old life, no one will be taking Bucky from him again anytime soon.

Who knows? Steve might even agree, to some extent, with Tony Stark on this one.

If anything, Captain, the guy who once told Tony "we should follow orders" has adopted a philosophy closer to Tony since "Winter Soldier".

They have kind of made this look like Cap is the bad guy. The whole point of civil war was that Cap was sticking with his values while it was Tony who was pushing to invade the privacy of people by forcing them to register (as it didn't matter to him because he was already out). This makes it look like Cap has just ignored all the rules for his friend and is willing to go against the government not because it is WRONG for the government to force citizens to put themselves in danger by exposing their true identity, but because his friend matters more.

Not sure I like the monumental difference to the original story line, it isn't even remaining true to the original conversation that tony and cap had in A2

Title: Captain America: Civil War Official Trailer #1 (2016) - Chris Evans, Scarlett Johansson Movie HD
Comment:
It's sad Marvel couldn't stay true to that comics due to character and plot constraints brought about them not owning all of their characters. They had to use Bucky here where he shouldn't have been. The real reason behind it is more political.  Due to the increasing numbers of B-list heroes who have been blatantly failing in saving people, the government issued a mandate that all past, present and future "inhumans/Enhanceds" must be registered and be screened fit to to be a hero with it they also have to surrender their secret identities. Capt. America saw this as a liability rather than a fix. What if the enemy managed to hack said registry and used all that info against the heroes. He opposed the mandate backed up by the Avengers and affiliated heroes

Iron Man and Ant-man saw this a sign of stability. They were tired of B-list heroes left unchecked who more bad than good and they also saw earth-foreign entities as a liability and could not be fully trusted.  What they wanted was a sense of order that could help everyday citizens rather than wannabe heroes running amok.


All in all, Cant wait for this! whoo!
